<h2>Image Format Converter - Convert JPG, PNG, WebP, GIF Online</h2>
    <p>The Image Format Converter lets you convert images between all major formats including JPEG, PNG, WebP, and GIF — directly in your browser with no upload required. Change image formats instantly while preserving quality, adjusting dimensions, and customizing background color for transparent images.</p>

    <h3>What Is the Image Format Converter?</h3>
    <p>This tool is a browser-based image conversion utility that uses the HTML5 Canvas API to re-encode images from one format to another. You upload an image in any supported format, choose your target format, configure optional settings like output dimensions and quality, and download the converted file. The entire process happens locally in your browser without any server-side processing.</p>
    <p>Different image formats have different strengths and are suited to different use cases. JPEG is the standard for photographs and complex images where small file size matters more than perfect quality. PNG is the go-to format for graphics, logos, screenshots, and images that require transparency. WebP is a modern format developed by Google that offers superior compression compared to both JPEG and PNG, making it the recommended choice for web images in 2024 and beyond. GIF supports animation and is still widely used for simple animated graphics.</p>
    <p>Converting between formats is a common task in web development, graphic design, and content creation. You might need to convert a PNG logo to WebP for your website, convert a JPEG photo to PNG to preserve transparency after editing, or convert a WebP image to JPEG for compatibility with older software. This tool handles all of these conversions instantly, with no quality loss beyond what is inherent to the target format's compression algorithm.</p>

    <h3>Supported Image Formats</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Convert between JPEG, PNG, WebP, and GIF formats with a single click — select your target format and the conversion happens instantly in the preview canvas.</li>
        <li>Adjustable output dimensions — set custom width and height values, or use the scale selector to output at 1x, 2x, 3x, or 4x the original size for retina displays.</li>
        <li>Quality control for JPEG and WebP — adjust the compression quality from 1–100% to balance file size against visual quality for lossy formats.</li>
        <li>Background color selection for transparency handling — when converting from a transparent format (PNG, WebP) to a non-transparent format (JPEG), choose white, black, a custom color, or keep transparency where supported.</li>
        <li>SVG input support — upload SVG vector files and convert them to raster formats at any resolution, perfect for creating PNG or WebP versions of vector logos and icons.</li>
        <li>Real-time canvas preview — see the converted image in the preview area before downloading, so you can verify the result looks correct.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to Use the Image Format Converter</h3>
    <p>Converting an image to a different format takes just a few seconds — follow these steps.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Step 1: Upload your image by clicking the upload area or dragging and dropping a file. Supported input formats include JPG, PNG, WebP, GIF, and SVG.</li>
        <li>Step 2: Select your target output format by clicking one of the format buttons: PNG, JPG, WebP, or GIF. The preview updates immediately to show the converted result.</li>
        <li>Step 3: Optionally adjust the output dimensions by entering custom width and height values, or use the scale selector to output at a specific multiplier of the original size.</li>
        <li>Step 4: For JPEG and WebP output, adjust the quality slider to control the compression level. For PNG and GIF, use the scale selector to control the output size.</li>
        <li>Step 5: Click the download button to save the converted image to your device in the selected format.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When to Convert Image Formats</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Web performance optimization — convert JPEG and PNG images to WebP format to reduce file sizes by 25–35% without visible quality loss, improving page load times and Core Web Vitals scores.</li>
        <li>Transparency handling — convert PNG images with transparent backgrounds to JPEG for use in contexts that do not support transparency, with control over the background fill color.</li>
        <li>Legacy compatibility — convert WebP images to JPEG or PNG for use in older software, email clients, or platforms that do not yet support the WebP format.</li>
        <li>SVG to raster conversion — convert SVG vector graphics to PNG or WebP at specific resolutions for use in contexts that require raster images, such as email templates or social media.</li>
        <li>Retina display assets — use the scale selector to output images at 2x or 3x resolution for use as high-DPI assets on retina displays and high-resolution screens.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Choosing the Right Image Format</h3>
    <p>When converting to WebP for web use, a quality setting of 80–85% typically produces files that are visually indistinguishable from the original JPEG while being 25–35% smaller. For lossless WebP (equivalent to PNG), the file size reduction is smaller but quality is perfectly preserved. Always test your converted images at actual display size to verify the quality is acceptable before deploying them to production.</p>
    <p>When converting transparent PNG images to JPEG, choose your background color carefully. White is the most common choice for images that will appear on white backgrounds, but if your image will appear on a dark background, a black or dark fill will look more natural. For images that will appear on a colored background, use the custom color picker to match the exact background color of your page or design.</p>
    <p>For SVG to raster conversion, set the output dimensions to the largest size you will need, as scaling up a raster image later will reduce quality. If you need the same image at multiple sizes, convert it multiple times at each required size rather than scaling up a smaller raster version. SVG files can be converted at any resolution without quality loss, so always start from the SVG source.</p>

    

    <h3>Images Converted Locally — No Upload</h3>
    <p>Format conversion runs in your browser. Your images are never uploaded to any server.</p>

            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What image formats can I convert between?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>The converter supports PNG, JPG/JPEG, WebP, BMP, and GIF (static). You can convert any of these to any other format. SVG conversion is not supported since SVG is a vector format and requires different handling.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">When should I use PNG vs JPG vs WebP?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Use PNG for images with transparency, text, logos, or screenshots where sharpness matters. Use JPG for photographs where some quality loss is acceptable in exchange for smaller file size. Use WebP for web images — it offers better compression than both PNG and JPG with similar quality.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does converting from JPG to PNG improve quality?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>No. Converting from a lossy format (JPG) to a lossless format (PNG) does not recover lost quality. The PNG will be larger but will not look better than the JPG. Quality can only be lost, not gained, through format conversion.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why is my WebP file larger than the original JPG?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>WebP is generally more efficient than JPG, but results vary by image content. If the original JPG was heavily compressed, a WebP at higher quality settings may be larger. Try reducing the WebP quality setting to get a smaller file.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I convert a GIF to a video format?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>This tool converts between image formats. For GIF to video conversion, use a dedicated video tool or FFmpeg. Converting a GIF to a static image format (PNG/JPG) will only capture the first frame.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>
</div>
</div>

</ToolLayout>